Multiplying two bit-vector expressions is a type error. Z3 should return "null" from Z3_mk_bvmul which is called from mkBvmul. Then Z3 sets an error flag, which the caller has to check. The C++, .NET, Java and OCaml wrappers check the error condition. Based on a repro attempt in C++ of your example, it appears that Z3 does indeed set the error flag and it is somehow not checked. Though, this seems odd given the withContextError and related wrappers that Z3.Monad seems to employ consistently.

    void crash() {
        context c;
        expr x(c), y(c), f(c);
        x = c.constant("x", c.int_sort());
        y = c.constant("y", c.int_sort());
        Z3_ast f1 = Z3_mk_bvmul(x.ctx(), x, y);
        c.check_error();              // ---- Z3 throws an exception here.
        f = expr(c, f1);
        std::cout << f << "\n";
        solver s(c);
        s.add(f);
        std::cout << s << "\n";
      }

The trouble with this sort of thing is templates need to be explicitly instantiated for them to make sense to pybind11 (i.e. your ``template <typename Range>`` constructor is not usable).

The only thing you *could* do is to characterize the concept of iterable types on the Python side:
```
  py::class_<Foo>(m, std::string("Foo").c_str())
    //Default no-args constructor
    .def(py::init())
    .def("__init__", [](Foo &f, py::iterable it){
        std::vector<int> data(py::len(it));
        int idx = 0;
        for (py::handle el : it)
            data[idx++] = el.cast<int>();
        new (&f) Foo(data);
    });
  py::class_<Bar>(m, std::string("Bar").c_str())
    //Default no-args constructor
    .def(py::init<std::list<int>&>())
    .def("__iter__", [](const Bar &b) { return py::make_iterator(b.begin(), b.end()); }, py::keep_alive<0, 1>())
    .def(py::init());
```
To use the ``iterable`` concept, you'll need to use the latest commit (7ca275588073428bff4d8b980c31b69087750410). Not sure if that gets you where you wanted to go, but that's the limits of what this library can do.

