As a workaround, you can do the following. Avoid referring to the class name within the class definition. For example, suppose the base class is

```python
class A(object):
  pass
```

Instead of defining the actor as

```python
@ray.actor
class B(A):
  def __init__(self):
    super(B, self).__init__()

# This fails.
B()
```

You can define it as follows.

```python
@ray.actor
class B(A):
  def __init__(self):
    A.__init__(self)

# This works.
B()
```

We need to compute checksum and then stream the file, but if it is going to be sent as encrypted, it must be a checksum of encrypted version of the file or B2 will reject it. We would either have to encrypt it twice or cache the file (or 100MB fragment?) somewhere (memory? probably not a good idea, I see people using b2 with systems having 1GB of RAM in total. Hard drive? Not so good either).

But this isn't how it should be in general. If B2 is supposed to be encryption friendly and at the same time it recommends using concurrent uploading, then it should not force us to do things like this. We should be able to upload files without specifying the checksum upfront, and we would verify the checksum on the client to see if one computed locally during streaming has matched the one computed by b2 service.

@nilayp, we spoke about the checksum a few months ago. You said that making it optional is on the list of things to be done "in the future". We have a contributor here who would like to implement encryption in CLI, but the mandatory checksum is a problem which will cause implementation headache and force DOUBLING the amount of I/O. Therefore I'd like to ask if you have any news on the optional checksum? Is it coming soon?

