> (...) We could of course also write our own handling of JS libraries into KolibriPluginBase to enforce it, furthermore writing our own handler for STATICFILES_FINDERS. Don't take my advice on any of this, since I haven't done it... but I think the latter might be cool :D

I don't know if this idea can float.... I was thinking that we could write our own (hopefully very simple) loader of static files that uses the plugin API to resolve which files a plugin supplies and where they are.. and that it makes sure to load them only once during template rendering using either sekizai or some other asset loading template tag (maybe one that we write).

So say there's a class method of your plugin's KolibriPluginBase inheritor... say we call it `static_files` and it returns a list of KolibriAsset and this will be picked up by our custom entry in STATICFILES_FINDERS:

```python

from . import __version__

class KolibriAsset:

    def __init__(self, identifier, version, src, dest, content_type="js", requires=()):
        self.type = type
        self.identifier = identifier
        self.version = version
        self.src = src
        self.dest = dest
        self.requires = requires

    def html_include(self, context_assets=[]):
        if self.type == "js":
            # Return all assets that haven't yet been loaded using the template context's list of loaded assets... something akin what Sekizai does.
            unloaded_requirements = filter(lambda x: x.identifier not in [asset.identifier for asset in context_assets], self.requires + [self])
            for asset_dest  in [x.dest for x in unloaded_requirements]:
                return "<script type='text/javascript'>{}</script>".format(
                    os.path.join(settings.STATIC_URL, self.asset_dest)
                )

# ...

class MyPlugin(KolibriPluginBase):

    @classmethod
    def static_files(cls):
        # jquery is a bad example because it's already in Core and plugins can expect this to exist no matter what.
        jquery = KolibriAsset("jquery", "8", "assets/jquery.js", "my_plugin/js/jquery.8.min.js", requires=())
        my_asset = KolibriAsset("my_plugin", __version__, "js/assets/my_plugin.js", "my_plugin/js/my_plugin.js", requires=(jquery,))

        return [
            jquery,
            my_asset
        ]

